One way to achieve both preserving the order of elements and having O(1) time complexity for insertion and retrieval operations is by using a combination of a Set and an Array in JavaScript.

Here's an example implementation:

```javascript
class OrderedSet {
  constructor() {
    this.set = new Set();
    this.array = [];
  }

  add(element) {
    if (!this.set.has(element)) {
      this.set.add(element);
      this.array.push(element);
    }
  }

  has(element) {
    return this.set.has(element);
  }

  delete(element) {
    if (this.set.has(element)) {
      this.set.delete(element);
      const index = this.array.indexOf(element);
      this.array.splice(index, 1);
    }
  }

  toArray() {
    return this.array;
  }
}
```

In this implementation, we maintain a Set `set` to check for element existence in O(1) time complexity. Additionally, we use an Array `array` to store the elements in the order they were added.

The `add` method checks if the element already exists in the Set. If not, it adds it to both the Set and the end of the Array.

The `has` method simply checks for element existence in the Set.

The `delete` method checks if the element exists in the Set. If it does, it deletes it from both the Set and the Array by finding its index using `indexOf` and splicing it out.

The `toArray` method returns the elements in the order they were added, preserving the original order of insertion.

With this implementation, both insertion (`add`) and retrieval (`has`, `toArray`) operations have a time complexity of O(1).

